Part I - Prosper Loan Data Exploration¶

by Joseph Eze¶

Introduction¶

This is a data set from Prosper, which is America’s first marketplace lending platform, with over $9 billion in funded loans. This data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others. This data dictionary explains the variables in the data set.

# convert CreditGrade, LoanStatus, EmploymentStatus  into ordered categorical types
ordinal_dict = {'CreditGrade': ['HR','E','D','C','B','A','AA'],
                'ProsperRating (Alpha)': ['HR','E','D','C','B','A','AA'],
                'IncomeRange': ['$0', '$1-24,999', '$25,000-49,999', '$50,000-74,999', '$75,000-99,999', 
                                '$100,000+', 'Not displayed', 'Not employed'],
                'LoanStatus': ['Current','Completed', 'FinalPaymentInProgress','Past Due (1-15 days)', 'Past Due (16-30 days)','Past Due (31-60 days)',
                               'Past Due (61-90 days)','Past Due (91-120 days)', 'Past Due (>120 days)', 'Cancelled','Chargedoff','Defaulted'],
                'EmploymentStatus': ['Employed','Full-time','Self-employed','Not available','Other','Part-time','Not employed','Retired']}

for var in ordinal_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True,
                                                categories = ordinal_dict[var])
    pld[var] = pld[var].astype(ordered_var)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113,937 loans recorded, with 80 variables which are mostly numeric.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The BorrowersAPR and the LoanStatus are the main features of my dataset.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

To support my investigation i would be looking at the ProsperRating, Occupation, StatedMonthlyIncome and the CreditGrade.

Univariate Exploration¶

In [7]:
#function to avoid repeating codes
def mycountplot(pld, xvar, order):
    #set plot dimensions
    plt.figure(figsize = (12, 10))
    #plot
    sb.countplot(data = pld, x = xvar, color = sb.color_palette()[0], order = order)
    #Add title and format
    plt.title(f'''Distribution of {xvar}''', fontsize = 14, weight = 'bold')
    #Add xlabel and format
    plt.xlabel(xvar, fontsize = 10, weight = 'bold')
    #Add ylabel and format
    plt.ylabel('Frequency'.title(), fontsize = 10, weight = 'bold')

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

There was an unusual distribution with the Borrower Rate, as it appeared unevenly distributed and skewed to the right, but after some transformation, it appeared multi-modal with lots of peaks, almost like the BorrowerAPR variable.

# plot matrix: sample 1000 Loan samples so that plots are clearer and they render faster

g = sb.PairGrid(data = pld_samp, vars = num_vars)

g.map_offdiag(sb.scatterplot, x_jitter= True, alpha = 0.08);

We can see a high positive correlation between our variable of interest (BorrowerAPR) with the BorrowerRate and the EstimatedEffectiveYield, another obeservation is the positive correlation between the LoanOriginalAmount and the MonthlyLoanPayment.

What is the Variable of interest (BorrowerAPR), MonthlyLoanPayment, StatedMonthlyIncome relationship with other categorical variables?¶

# plot matrix of numeric features against categorical features.

samples = np.random.choice(pld.shape[0], 3000, replace = False)
pld_samp = pld.loc[samples,:]

def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.boxplot(x, y, color = default_color)
    plt.xticks(rotation = 90)

plt.figure(figsize = [30, 30]);
g = sb.PairGrid(data = pld_samp, y_vars = ['BorrowerAPR', 'MonthlyLoanPayment', 'LoanOriginalAmount'], x_vars = cat_vars,
                height = 3, aspect = 1.2)
g.map(boxgrid)
plt.show();

<Figure size 2160x2160 with 0 Axes>

There seem to be a negative relationship between the ProperRating (Alpha) and our variable of interest (BorrowerAPR), also obeserved as expected that 'Not employed' have a higher borrower interest rate. The Self-employed or those with an income range with $100,000+ makes the top average monthly Loan payment.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

The AA rated loans tend to have lower annual interest rate compared to other ratings

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

The Not employed which i expected to make low monthly loan payment, averaged between 200 - 400 monthly and maintained between 0.15% and 0.30% annual interest rate.

Conclusions¶

In conclusion, The annual interest rate reduces with a higher prosper rating and also increases with the unemployed who also makes less monthly income.
